The results of this test are shown in Table 6. First, note that the recognition capability of the method in the case of random perturbations of the points’ locations on the curve deteriorates differently for the four curves: the elliptic curve and the quartic curve with tacnode show poor results starting from σ=0.04𝜎0.04\sigma=0.04, while in the case of the other curves the algorithm performs relatively well even with σ=0.15𝜎0.15\sigma=0.15.
Next, we also look at the number of exact recognitions of the four given curves. The Descartes Folium behaves well for small values of σ𝜎\sigma, with exact recognition rates of 24%percent2424\%, 12%percent1212\%, 4%percent44\%, 1%percent11\%, 1%percent11\% for σ=0.01,0.02,0.04,0.05,0.06𝜎0.010.020.040.050.06\sigma=0.01,~{}0.02,~{}0.04,~{}0.05,~{}0.06, respectively. These values may seem low but, if combined with those shown in Table 6, they indicate that even when not perfect the recognition is still very accurate. The elliptic curve case shows high rates of exact recognition (89%percent8989\%, 44%percent4444\%, 14%percent1414\%, 10%percent1010\%, 4%percent44\%, 1%percent11\% for σ=0.01,0.02,0.04,0.05,0.06,0.1𝜎0.010.020.040.050.060.1\sigma=0.01,~{}0.02,~{}0.04,~{}0.05,~{}0.06,~{}0.1, respectively), but, at the same time, when the recognition goes wrong, the parameters values we found rather differ from a=−4𝑎4a=-4, b=7𝑏7b=7, also in the case of small values of the standard deviation σ𝜎\sigma, thus justifying the overall non-optimal behavior shown in Table 6.
In the case of the quartic curve with triple point, we never find the exact parameters a=15𝑎15a=\frac{1}{5}, b=12𝑏12b=\frac{1}{2}, but we get parameters values rather close to them for all the considered values of σ𝜎\sigma.
The quartic curve with tacnode presents an 11%percent1111\% rate of exact recognition for σ=0.01𝜎0.01\sigma=0.01, while for higher values of σ𝜎\sigma the recognition of the exact parameters a=1𝑎1a=1, b=8𝑏8b=8 systematically fails.
